rect results in user code without throwing"}],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":0,"created_at":"2024-11-05T10:18:46Z","updated_at":"2024-11-05T10:18:46Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"active_lock_reason":null,"body":"The `searchsorted*` implementation currently assumes that `midpoint(lo, hi) <= hi` and such, which wouldn't be true if the values wrap around before the call (i.e. if `hi < low` in the call). The indexing is also assumed to be `@inbounds`, which would usually not be true with wrapping, and would lead to segfaults.

https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/blob/11cd8098714e7944fc899905114bdee404044f42/base/sort.jl#L223-L240

Currently, these methods are specialized in `OffsetArrays` to avoid such errors, but I wonder if the `Base` methods may be fixed to account for offset indices. In particular, wrappers of `OffsetArray`s would still hit these fallback methods, so it would be good for these to be correct.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/56457/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/56457/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null}}

